load ../selective-undo.maude

--- The history for every fixture: e1 wrote p1; e2 and e3 wrote p2; e3 read
--- both e1's and e2's writes. Undoing p1 therefore selects only e1 while
--- the retained e3 read e1's output; undoing p2 selects e2 AND e3, so
--- e3's read of e2 stays inside the selection.

--- The hazard demonstrated: the naive path filter accepts the p1 undo even
--- though the plan strands e3 -- the accepted proposal coexists with a
--- history in which the stranding test is TRUE.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SELECTIVE-UNDO :
  undoReq(p1) hist(wrote(e1, p1) ; wrote(e2, p2) ; wrote(e3, p2),
                   readOf(e3, e1) ; readOf(e3, e2))
  =>* proposal(naivePlan, p1) hist(WS:WSet, RS:RSet)
  such that strands(selByPath(p1, WS:WSet), RS:RSet) = true .

--- Bite: the dependency-closure planner NEVER accepts the p1 undo -- a
--- later retained edit read the undone writes.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SELECTIVE-UNDO :
  undoReq(p1) hist(wrote(e1, p1) ; wrote(e2, p2) ; wrote(e3, p2),
                   readOf(e3, e1) ; readOf(e3, e2))
  =>* proposal(checkedPlan, p1) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Coverage: it refuses honestly instead.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SELECTIVE-UNDO :
  undoReq(p1) hist(wrote(e1, p1) ; wrote(e2, p2) ; wrote(e3, p2),
                   readOf(e3, e1) ; readOf(e3, e2))
  =>* rejected(p1) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Coverage: the p2 undo selects e2 and e3 together; e3's read of e2 lies
--- INSIDE the selection, so nothing is stranded and the closure-shaped
--- check accepts.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SELECTIVE-UNDO :
  undoReq(p2) hist(wrote(e1, p1) ; wrote(e2, p2) ; wrote(e3, p2),
                   readOf(e3, e1) ; readOf(e3, e2))
  =>* proposal(checkedPlan, p2) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Bite against over-refusal: the p2 undo is never rejected -- the check
--- is the dependency closure, not the mere existence of reads.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SELECTIVE-UNDO :
  undoReq(p2) hist(wrote(e1, p1) ; wrote(e2, p2) ; wrote(e3, p2),
                   readOf(e3, e1) ; readOf(e3, e2))
  =>* rejected(p2) RESIDUAL:Cfg .
